In this notebook, we will predict the likelihood of a heart attack.

Task 2¶

2.¶

As we can see, explanations for the first three observations from the dataset vary for age feature, but are very similar for cholesterol if we use Random Forest Classifier.

This is different for the Logistic Regression model - the explanations for age are similar here. They also increase while for Random Forest they rather decrease...

3.¶

Between the age of 40 and 70, the explanations diverge. When the one increases, the other one decreases.

4.¶

The results obtained on the mean of the dataset and the cholesterol feature are similar, but the PDP seems to be slightly less stable with its predictions. They are also a little bit lower.

5.¶

The PDP of Logistic Regression is smooth, almost flat, completely different towards the PDP of Random Forest, but this is something expectable for regression. Both PDPs show that the predictions of not getting a heart attack are higher for lower cholesterol. The peaks of Random Forest's PDP give us very important information about the least and most optimal values of cholesterol.

X = df.drop(columns='output')
X = pd.get_dummies(X, columns=['sex', 'cp', 'slp'], drop_first=True)
y = df.output

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.33, random_state=42)
In [ ]:
rfc_model = RandomForestClassifier()
rfc_model.fit(X_train, y_train)
In [ ]:
lr_model = LogisticRegression()
lr_model.fit(X_train, y_train)
